<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:20151007_174039-S.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https:=
//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/20151007_174039-S.jpg/3=
30px-20151007_174039-S.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=3D"180"=
 class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1291" data-file-height=3D"775=
"></a><figcaption>Leaving some change on the restaurant table is one way of=
 giving a gratuity to the restaurant staff.</figcaption></figure>
<p>A <b>gratuity</b> (often called a <b>tip</b>) is a sum of money customar=
ily given by a customer to certain <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Service_sector" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Service sector">service sec=
tor</a> workers such as hospitality for the service they have performed, in=
 addition to the basic price of the service.
</p><p>Tips and their amount are a matter of social <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Convention_(norm)" title=3D"Convention (norm)">custom</a>=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Etiquette" title=3D"Etiquette=
">etiquette</a>, and the custom varies between countries and between settin=
gs. In some countries, it is customary to tip <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Waiting_staff" title=3D"Waiting staff">servers</a> in bars and =
restaurants, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxi" title=3D"Taxi">=
taxi</a> drivers, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tattoo_artist" t=
itle=3D"Tattoo artist">tattoo artists</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Hairdresser" title=3D"Hairdresser">hair stylists</a> and so on. Ho=
wever, in some places tipping is not expected and may be discouraged or con=
sidered insulting.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The customary a=
mount of a tip can be a specific range or a certain percentage of the bill =
based on the perceived quality of the service given.
</p><p>It is illegal to offer tips to some groups of workers, such as U.S. =
government workers<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5CFR2635_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-5CFR2635-2"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> and more widely <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Police_office=
r" title=3D"Police officer">police officers</a>, as the tips may be regarde=
d as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bribery" title=3D"Bribery">br=
ibery</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A fixed percentage <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mandatory_tipping" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Mandatory tipping">service charge</a> is sometimes added to bil=
ls in restaurants and similar establishments. Tipping may not be expected w=
hen a fee is explicitly charged for the service.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-usatoda=
y.com_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gra=
tuity#cite_note-usatoday.com-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Giving a tip is typically irreversible, differentiating it from the =
reward mechanism of a placed order, which can be refunded.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-Commerce_Clearing_House_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-Commerce_Clearing_House-5"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
From a theoretical economic point of view, gratuities may solve the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal%E2%80%93agent_problem" title=3D=
"Principal=E2=80=93agent problem">principal=E2=80=93agent problem</a><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-videbeck_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-videbeck-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (the situation in w=
hich an agent, such as a server, is working for a principal, such as a rest=
aurant owner or manager) and many managers believe that tips provide incent=
ive for greater worker effort.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-graham_7-0" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-graham-7=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> However, studies of the practice in America suggest that tippi=
ng is often discriminatory or arbitrary: workers receive different levels o=
f gratuity based on factors such as age, sex, race, hair color and even bre=
ast size, and the size of the gratuity is found to be only tenuously relate=
d to the quality of service.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-freak_8-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-freak-8"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Etymology_and_history">Etym=
ology and history</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DGratuity&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Et=
ymology and history"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Waiters.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><i=
mg src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2d/Waiters=
.jpg/250px-Waiters.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"220" height=3D"130" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1644" data-file-height=3D"972"></=
a><figcaption>Waiters in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wroc%C5%8=
2aw" title=3D"Wroc=C5=82aw">Breslau</a>, Germany (now Wroc=C5=82aw, Poland)=
, in 1913</figcaption></figure>
<p>According to the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oxford_Engl=
ish_Dictionary" title=3D"Oxford English Dictionary">Oxford English Dictiona=
ry</a></i>, the word "tip" originated as a slang term and its etymology is =
unclear. According to the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Onlin=
e_Etymology_Dictionary" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Online Etymology Dic=
tionary">Online Etymology Dictionary</a></i>, the meaning "give a small pre=
sent of money" began around 1600, and the meaning "give a gratuity to" is f=
irst attested in 1706.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-etymonline.com_9-0" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-etymonli=
ne.com-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-todayifoundout.com_10-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-today=
ifoundout.com-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The noun in this sense is from 1755. The term=
 in the sense of "to give a gratuity" first appeared in the 18th century. I=
t derived from an earlier sense of <i>tip</i>, meaning "to give; to hand, p=
ass", which originated in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thie=
ves%27_cant" title=3D"Thieves' cant">thieves' cant</a> in the 17th century.=
 This sense may have derived from the 16th-century "tip" meaning "to strike=
 or hit smartly but lightly" (which may have derived from the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Low_German" title=3D"Low German">Low German</a>=
 <i>tippen</i>, "to tap"), but this derivation is "very uncertain".<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-oed2_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-oed2-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The word "tip" was first =
used as a verb in 1707 in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_F=
arquhar" title=3D"George Farquhar">George Farquhar</a>'s play <i><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Beaux%27_Stratagem" title=3D"The Beaux' =
Stratagem">The Beaux' Stratagem</a></i>. Farquhar used the term after it ha=
d been "used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Criminal" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Criminal">criminal</a> circles as a word meant to im=
ply the unnecessary and gratuitous gifting of something somewhat taboo, lik=
e a joke, or a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sure_bet" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Sure bet">sure bet</a>, or illicit money exchanges."<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The etymology for the synonym for tipping, "gratuity", dates back ei=
ther to the 1520s, from "graciousness", from the French <i>gratuit=C3=A9</i=
> (14th century) or directly from Medieval Latin <i>gratuitas</i>, "free gi=
ft", probably from earlier Latin <i>gratuitus</i>, "free, freely given". Th=
e meaning "money given for favor or services" is first attested in the 1530=
s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-etymonline.com_9-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-etymonline.com-9"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 In some languages, the term translates to "drink money" or similar: for ex=
ample <i>pourboire</i> in French, <i>Trinkgeld</i> in German, <i>drikkepeng=
e</i> in Danish, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drinksilver" t=
itle=3D"Drinksilver">drinksilver</a></i> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Middle_Scots" title=3D"Middle Scots">Middle Scots</a>, and <i>nap=
iwek</i> in Polish. This comes from a custom of inviting a servant to drink=
 a glass in honour of the guest, and paying for it, in order for the guests=
 to show generosity among each other. The term <i>bibalia</i> in Latin was =
recorded in 1372.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The practice of tipping began in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Tudor_England" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tudor England">Tudor En=
gland</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-nytimes.com_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-nytimes.com-14"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> In medieval times, tipping was a master-serf custom wherein a servant=
 would receive extra money for having performed superbly well.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gra=
tuity#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> By the 17th century, it was expected that o=
vernight guests to private homes would provide sums of money, known as vail=
s, to the host's servants. Soon afterwards, customers began tipping in Lond=
on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coffee_house" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Coffee house">coffeehouses</a> and other commercial establish=
ments".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-nytimes.com_14-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-nytimes.com-14"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p><p>The practice was imported from Europe to America in the 1850s and 18=
60s by Americans who wanted to seem aristocratic.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_no=
te-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> However, until the early 20th century, Americans viewed =
tipping as inconsistent with the values of an egalitarian, democratic socie=
ty, as the origins of tipping were premised upon <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Noblesse_oblige" title=3D"Noblesse oblige">noblesse oblige</=
a>, which promoted tipping as a means to establish social status to inferio=
rs.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Segrave1998_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-Segrave1998-17"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Six American states passed laws that made tipping illegal. Enforcement of =
anti-tipping laws was problematic.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Segrave1998_17-1" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_not=
e-Segrave1998-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The earliest of these laws was passed in 1909=
 (Washington), and the last of these laws was repealed in 1926 (Mississippi=
).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Segrave1998_17-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-Segrave1998-17"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  S=
ome have argued that "The original workers that were not paid anything by t=
heir employers were newly freed slaves" and that "This whole concept of not=
 paying them anything and letting them live on tips carried over from slave=
ry."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_not=
e-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Also, proprietors regarded tips as equivalent to bribing an employee=
 to do something that was otherwise forbidden, such as tipping a waiter to =
get an extra large portion of food.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Segrave1998_17-3" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_no=
te-Segrave1998-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, the introduction of <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prohibition" title=3D"Prohibition">Prohibition</a=
> in the US in 1919 had an enormous impact on hotels and restaurants, who l=
ost the revenue of selling alcoholic beverages. The resulting financial pre=
ssure caused proprietors to welcome tips, as a way of supplementing employe=
e wages.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Mentzer2013_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-Mentzer2013-21"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> Contrary to popular belief, tipping did not arise because of servers'=
 low wages, because the occupation of waiter (server) was fairly well paid =
in the era when tipping became institutionalized.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Mentze=
r2013_21-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gr=
atuity#cite_note-Mentzer2013-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Reasons_for_tipping">Reason=
s for tipping</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DGratuity&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Reaso=
ns for tipping"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>Tipping researcher Michael Lynn identifies five motivations for tipping:=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Showing off</li>
<li>To supplement the server's income and make them happy</li>
<li>For improved future service</li>
<li>To avoid disapproval from the server</li>
<li>A sense of duty</li></ul>
<p>A 2009 academic paper by Steven Holland calls tipping "an effective mech=
anism for risk sharing and welfare improvement" which reduces the risk face=
d by a service customer, because the customer can decide whether or not to =
tip.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2=
3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Tipping is sometimes given=
 as an example of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal%E2=
%80%93agent_problem" title=3D"Principal=E2=80=93agent problem">principal=E2=
=80=93agent problem</a> in economics. One example is a restaurant owner who=
 engages servers to act as agents on his behalf.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-videbec=
k_6-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuit=
y#cite_note-videbeck-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In some cases, "[c]ompensation agreeme=
nts [can] increase worker effort [...] if compensation is [...] tied to the=
 firm's success" and one example of such a compensation agreement is waiter=
s and waitresses who are paid tips.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-graham_7-1" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-gra=
ham-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> Studies show however that, in the real world, the size of=
 the tip is only weakly correlated with the quality of the service and othe=
r effects dominate.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-freak_8-1" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-freak-8"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Tronc">Tronc</h2><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGratuity&amp;action=3Dedit=
&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Tronc"><span>edit</span></a><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A tronc is an arrangement for the pooling and distribution to employees =
of tips, gratuities and/or service charges in the hotel and catering trade.=
 The person who distributes monies from the tronc is known as the troncmast=
er. Where a tronc exists in the UK, responsibility for deducting <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pay-as-you-earn_tax" title=3D"Pay-as-you-ear=
n tax">pay-as-you-earn taxes</a> from the distribution may lie with the tro=
ncmaster rather than the employer.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-24"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up><sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Mandatory_tipping">Mandator=
y tipping</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGr=
atuity&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Mandatory =
tipping"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mandatory_tipping" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mandatory tipping">Mandatory tipping</a></div=
>
<p>Tipping may not be expected when a fee is explicitly charged for the ser=
vice.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-usatoday.com_4-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-usatoday.com-4"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Service_charge" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Service charge">service charge</a> is sometimes added to bil=
ls in restaurants and similar establishments. Attempts to hide service char=
ge by obscuring the line on the receipt have been reported.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratui=
ty#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A service charge, or fee assessed, is determin=
ed by and paid directly to the company. The charges may be for services ren=
dered, administrative fees, or processing cost.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Service_=
Charge_27-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G=
ratuity#cite_note-Service_Charge-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2=
7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the United States, criminal charges were dropped in two separate =
cases over non-payment of mandatory gratuities. Courts ruled that automatic=
 does not mean mandatory.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-nytimes_2004-09-15_29-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-nytimes_2004-09-15-29"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> Some cruise lines charge their patrons US$10 per day in mandatory tippi=
ng;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> this does not include extra=
 gratuities for alcoholic beverages.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-usatoday.com_4-2" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_n=
ote-usatoday.com-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"By_region">By region</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGratuity&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: By region"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_tipping_cust=
oms_by_country" title=3D"List of tipping customs by country">List of tippin=
g customs by country</a></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Criticisms">Criticisms</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGratuity&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Criticisms"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Inconsistency_of_percentage=
-based_gratuities">Inconsistency of percentage-based gratuities</h3><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGratuity&amp;action=3De=
dit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Inconsistency of percentage-bas=
ed gratuities"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:William_Powell_Frith_The_crossing_sweeper_1893.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-de=
scription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb=
/3/3b/William_Powell_Frith_The_crossing_sweeper_1893.jpg/250px-William_Powe=
ll_Frith_The_crossing_sweeper_1893.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"200" he=
ight=3D"244" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1130" data-file-h=
eight=3D"1380"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cro=
ssing_sweeper" title=3D"Crossing sweeper">Crossing sweepers</a> cleared the=
 way for rich people to cross the road without dirtying their clothes and t=
hey were normally tipped for this service (London, 1893), while the modern =
version of this service are so-called '<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Squeegee_man" title=3D"Squeegee man">squeegee men</a>' who clean vehic=
le windshields while stopped for traffic lights (often without the consent =
of the driver).</figcaption></figure>
<p>In countries where tipping is the norm, some employers pay workers with =
the expectation that their wages will be supplemented by tips. Some have cr=
iticized the inherent "social awkwardness" in transactions that involve tip=
ping, the inconsistency of tipping for some services but not similar ones, =
and the irrationality of basing tips on price, rather than the amount and q=
uality of service (a customer pays a larger tip to a server bringing a lobs=
ter rather than a hamburger, for example).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-31">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Travellers_following_home_r=
ather_than_local_customs">Travellers following home rather than local custo=
ms</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGratuity&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Travellers follow=
ing home rather than local customs"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Some nationalities, such as people from the United States, are used to p=
aying tips, and often do so even when they visit countries where this is le=
ss of a norm. In contrast, tourists from such countries may neglect or even=
 refuse to pay tips when they visit countries such as the US where tips are=
 expected. This is particularly common in American cities along the Canadia=
n border, and is seen as a problem by many in the hospitality sector.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Gratuity#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Discomfort">Discomfort</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGratuity&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Discomfort"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Tipping might be discomforting to some people because it adds the necess=
ity of figuring out the tip amount each time, which is made harder by the f=
act that the tip amount the service provider is hoping to receive, is in ge=
neral, unknown to the customer. A lack of or too low a tip might offend the=
 service provider, this adds the discomfort of creating an unpleasant socia=
l encounter to each service transaction which might involve the expectation=
 of tipping.
Tipping might be discomforting also to some service providers as they might=
 view it as derogating to their occupation, as "a token of inferiority".<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> William Scott in his <i>The Itchi=
ng Palm</i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-The_Itching_Palm_34-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-The_Itching_Palm=
-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> study wrote: "The relation of a man giving a tip and a man=
 accepting it is as undemocratic as the relation of master and slave. A cit=
izen in a republic ought to stand shoulder to shoulder with every other cit=
izen, with no thought of cringing, without an assumption of superiority or =
an acknowledgment of inferiority."
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Discrimination">Discriminat=
ion</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGratuity=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Discrimination"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<p>In the episode of the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freako=
nomics_Radio" title=3D"Freakonomics Radio">Freakonomics</a></i> <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Podcast" title=3D"Podcast">podcast</a> Lynn f=
ound that "attractive waitresses get better tips than less attractive waitr=
esses. Men=E2=80=99s appearance, not so important". Lynn's research also fo=
und that "blondes get better tips than brunettes. Slender women get better =
tips than heavier women. Large breasted women get better tips than smaller =
breasted women. Surprisingly, at least in the studies I=E2=80=99ve done, wo=
men in their 30s get better tips than either younger or older women.=E2=80=
=9D A woman server interviewed for the podcast episode stated: "lost my job=
 because my manager said that I didn=E2=80=99t fit the look of the company,=
 or the restaurant. So I don=E2=80=99t know if it was because I=E2=80=99m a=
 lot more curvier than the other girls or because my skin is darker. I don=
=E2=80=99t know".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-freak_8-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-freak-8"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Lynn states of tipping: "It=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Discrimination" title=3D"Discrimination">discriminatory</a>. Yes=
, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_the_Uni=
ted_States" title=3D"Supreme Court of the United States">Supreme Court</a> =
has ruled that even neutral business practices that are not intended to dis=
criminate, if they have the effect of adversely impacting a <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protected_group" title=3D"Protected group">protec=
ted class</a> are illegal. And so it=E2=80=99s not inconceivable to me that=
 there will be a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Class-action_laws=
uit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Class-action lawsuit">class-action laws=
uit</a> on the part of ethnic minority waiters and waitresses claiming disc=
rimination in terms of employment. And it=E2=80=99s conceivable that tippin=
g might be declared illegal on that basis.=E2=80=9D<sup id=3D"cite_ref-frea=
k_8-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuit=
y#cite_note-freak-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Tipflation">Tipflation</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGratuity&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Tipflation"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tipflation" title=3D=
"Tipflation">Tipflation</a></div>
<p>In the United States since the 2020s, some argue that there is an increa=
sing expectation for customers to tip more frequently and at higher rates. =
This is often due to the influence of digital payment systems and changing =
service industry norms.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratuity#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
